import java.util.HashMap;
import java.util.Map;

public class OrderProcessor {

    private Map<String, Integer> priceList = new HashMap<>();

    // Method to add products and their prices to the map
    public void addProduct(String productName, int price) {
        priceList.put(productName, price);
    }

    // Method to split the order string and retrieve the price
    public int getOrderPrice(String orderString) {
        String[] orderData = orderString.split("\\s+");
        String[] productDetails = orderData[0].split("–");
        int productPrice = priceList.get(productDetails[1]);
        int orderPrice = Integer.parseInt(orderData[1]) * productPrice;
        return orderPrice;
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        OrderProcessor processor = new OrderProcessor();

        // Add products and their prices
        processor.addProduct("Apple", 1.50);
        processor.addProduct("Banana", 0.75);

        // Process an order string
        String orderString = "Apple–1";
        int price = processor.getOrderPrice(orderString);
        System.out.println("Order Price: $" + price); // Output: Order Price: $1.25
    }
}
```

In this example, we have a `OrderProcessor` class with two methods:
1. `addProduct`: This method adds products and their prices to a map.
2. `getOrderPrice`: This method splits the order string, retrieves the product name from the first part, finds the corresponding price in the map, and calculates the total order price.

The `main` method demonstrates how to use the `OrderProcessor` class by adding products and processing an order string.

